ZenPhoto

Target IP: 192.168.153.41

Scanning



There are four TCP ports open on the target machine as shown above.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this application. Viewing the source-code of the web-page does not reveal anything useful either.


Performing a directory search using the command gobuster dir -u http://192.168.153.41 -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x php,html,txt returns an interesting directory called /test.


Browsing to /test displays the web application above. It seems to be running Zen Photo.


Performing a directory search using feroxbuster with the command feroxbuster -u http://192.168.153.41/test/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt -d 2 -x php,html,txt,zip against this /test/ directory returned the interesting result above. The robots.txt is interesting.


The entries above are displayed at the robots.txt page.


The /test/zp-data is interesting as it contains log files; however, I cannot access them! Testing for LFI on zp-config.php did not reveal anything useful either.


I went back to the index page and viewed the source-code. That's where I found the version of the application which is 1.4.1.4.


And doing a Google search shows this application version is vulnerable to RCE.

Exploitation


I saved a copy of the exploit php/webapps/18083.php using searchsploit on my machine and ran it against the target machine.


I managed to obtain a reverse shell connection from the target machine to my local machine on port 8443. In the picture above, the exploit is being run on the top terminal. The terminal on bottom is where I obtained a reverse shell connection. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


The file zp-config.php contains the MySQL credential root:hola.


There is an interesting table called zp_administrators. However, I am unable to crack this password hash of the user admin.


The target machine is running an out-dated version of Linux. Maybe it is vulnerable to kernel exploits?



I finally managed to obtain a root shell by using the exploit above. I tried using a few different exploits, but I had no luck except for this one.

Flags


The local.txt flag once I gained a foothold on the target machine.


The proof.txt flag once I used a kernel exploit to spawn a root shell.
